; =====================================================================
; ApertoMemory v0.2 — CDDL Schema (RFC 8610)
; Serialisation: deterministic CBOR (RFC 8949 s4.2)
; Normative reference: draft-ferro-apertomemory (see /draft)
; Conformance is defined by /test-vectors/v2 (vector set 001-014):
;   reproducing the byte strings is necessary but NOT sufficient - six
;   of the fourteen vectors are refusal cases.
; =====================================================================
;
; WHO THIS SCHEMA BINDS
;
; The rules below define what a conformant PRODUCER emits. They are not
; the whole of conformance, and a consumer that merely rejects whatever
; fails to validate is not conformant either.
;
; A consumer has a second, separate obligation: to handle input that
; does NOT match this schema without failing catastrophically. Hostile
; and corrupt objects exist, and refusing to read a whole container
; because one object inside it is malformed is a denial of service on
; the user's entire memory.
;
; So: a validator SHOULD reject a payload carrying an empty custody
; record (test vector 014), because no producer may write one - and an
; implementation MUST still read the container it lives in, degrade that
; object's trust, and carry on. Both are required. Neither substitutes
; for the other.
;
; Where the two obligations meet, the prose sections below say which is
; which explicitly.
; =====================================================================

; ---------------------------------------------------------------------
; 1. What a Blind Server is allowed to see (root rule)
; ---------------------------------------------------------------------
sealed-object = {
  1 => bstr .size 16,   ; id: 128-bit random (NOT UUIDv7: time-ordered
                        ;   ids leak creation-time metadata)
  2 => bstr .size 16,   ; scope_id: opaque random identifier
  3 => uint,            ; format_version (current = 2; 1 = legacy)
  4 => bstr,            ; COSE_Encrypt0 (AES-256-GCM, COSE alg 3, MTI;
                        ;   alg 24 OPTIONAL) whose plaintext is a
                        ;   COSE_Sign1 (EdDSA) over memory-payload.
                        ;   Both carry envelope-aad as external_aad.
  ? 5 => bstr .size 16, ; dek_wrap_ref (optional)
}
; Sign-then-encrypt: the signature lives INSIDE the ciphertext.
; The server can neither learn nor verify authorship; verification
; happens client-side after decryption.

; ---------------------------------------------------------------------
; 2. The two bindings (new in format_version 2)
; ---------------------------------------------------------------------
; v1 objects carried no cryptographic relationship between a signature,
; the author it claimed, and the cleartext envelope around it. Both are
; now bound.

; ENVELOPE BINDING. This structure is supplied as COSE external_aad to
; BOTH the COSE_Sign1 and the COSE_Encrypt0 of every object. It is never
; transmitted: it is reconstructed by the reader from the cleartext
; envelope, so rewriting id, scope_id or format_version invalidates the
; AEAD tag. Version downgrade is detected for the same reason.
envelope-aad = [
  uint,                 ; format_version, as it appears in the envelope
  bstr .size 16,        ; id, as it appears in the envelope
  bstr .size 16,        ; scope_id, as it appears in the envelope
]
; Serialised as deterministic CBOR before use.

; AUTHOR BINDING. The author_key_id inside the signed payload MUST equal
; the first 8 bytes of SHA-256 over the public key that verified the
; signature. A signer therefore cannot claim an identity it cannot
; prove. The kid in the COSE protected header MUST carry the same value:
; both are signed, so a disagreement between them makes the object
; self-inconsistent and it MUST be refused (test vector 010).

; ---------------------------------------------------------------------
; 3. The signed payload
; ---------------------------------------------------------------------
memory-payload = {
  1 => mem-type,
  2 => tstr,            ; content: UTF-8 text (v0.2: text only)
  3 => confidence,      ; 0.0 .. 1.0
  4 => provenance,
  5 => trust-level,     ; INFORMATIONAL ONLY - see s4
  ? 6 => [* tstr],      ; tags
  7 => timestamps,      ; SEMANTIC times — MUST NOT appear in cleartext
  ? 8 => embedding,     ; RESERVED - see s3.1. MUST travel encrypted only
  ? 9 => epoch-seconds, ; expires_at. RESERVED - see s3.1
  ? 10 => {* tstr => any}, ; extensions. RESERVED - see s3.1
  ? 20 => custody,      ; present iff this object was re-sealed - see s5
  * uint => any,        ; unrecognised keys MUST be preserved on rewrite
}

; --- s3.1 Reserved keys -----------------------------------------------
; Keys 8, 9 and 10 are reserved and carry the shapes given above, but no
; v0.2 implementation interprets them: they are read, preserved verbatim
; on rewrite, and otherwise ignored. Consumers MUST NOT rely on them.
;
; expires_at (9) in particular is NOT enforced. An expired object is
; still returned. Do not build an expiry guarantee on it until an
; implementation states that it honours the field.
;
; Key 5 of sealed-object (dek_wrap_ref) is likewise reserved: no v0.2
; implementation emits or reads it.
;
; This section exists because a schema that describes a field nobody
; implements is the same defect as a README that claims a defence the
; code does not provide. Stating the gap is the fix.

mem-type = &( episodic: 1, semantic: 2, procedural: 3 )

confidence = float .ge 0.0
; The normative range is 0.0 .. 1.0 inclusive. CDDL tooling does not
; express a closed float interval portably - chained control operators
; and float ranges are rejected by common validators - so the upper
; bound is stated here and enforced by test vector 013 rather than by
; the schema. A producer MUST NOT write above 1.0.
; A producer MUST NOT write a value outside this range. A consumer that
; reads one MUST NOT propagate it: the object is authentic, so it is not
; refused, but the value is reported as absent and the schema violation
; flagged. Consumers rank memories by confidence, and propagating an
; out-of-range value would let a non-conformant producer dominate every
; ranking (test vector 013).

provenance = {
  1 => tstr,            ; producing tool (e.g. "amem-cli/0.2")
  2 => bstr .size 8,    ; author_key_id: first 8 bytes of SHA-256 of
                        ;   the author's Ed25519 public key. Bound to
                        ;   the verifying key - see s1.
  ? 3 => tstr,          ; session identifier
}

trust-level = &( self: 1, trusted: 2, third-party: 3, unverified: 4 )
; third-party (3) is reserved: v0.2 derives only self, trusted and
; unverified. It is retained for wire compatibility with v1 payloads.

timestamps = { 1 => epoch-seconds, ? 2 => epoch-seconds }  ; created, updated

epoch-seconds = uint
; Seconds since 1970-01-01T00:00:00Z, as a BARE uint.
;
; Deliberately not the CDDL prelude "time", which is #6.1(number) - a
; tag-1 epoch datetime. Every object written so far, and every test
; vector, carries an untagged integer. Tagging them now would invalidate
; every existing vault to gain nothing: the field is unambiguous as it
; stands. The schema records what the format is, not what it might have
; been.
;
; This divergence was found by validating the vectors with a second,
; independent CDDL implementation. The first one did not enforce the
; tag, and the schema quietly disagreed with every object in existence.
embedding = { 1 => tstr, 2 => [* float] } ; model, vector

; ---------------------------------------------------------------------
; 3.2 What a producer MUST refuse to write
; ---------------------------------------------------------------------
; The rules above constrain what a consumer does with a bad value. A
; conformant producer refuses to create one in the first place, and
; MUST fail rather than emit an object where:
;
;   * confidence is absent, NaN, infinite, or outside 0.0 .. 1.0;
;   * content is not a non-empty UTF-8 string;
;   * mem-type is outside the enumeration.
;
; A consumer, by contrast, is deliberately more tolerant on read: it
; reports an unrecognised mem-type verbatim rather than refusing the
; object, because refusing to read is a worse failure than reporting an
; unknown type. Strict on write, lenient on read.

; ---------------------------------------------------------------------
; 4. Trust is derived, never declared
; ---------------------------------------------------------------------
; Field 5 above is carried for wire compatibility and MUST NOT be read
; as authoritative. A consumer derives trust from WHICH KEY verified the
; signature:
;
;   verified by the vault owner's key          -> self
;   verified by an accepted third-party key    -> trusted
;   not verified, or verified by a key that is
;     no longer accepted                       -> unverified
;
; Trust is evaluated at read time against the current set of accepted
; keys, and MUST NOT be frozen into the object: revoking a key downgrades
; every memory attributed to it, with no rewrite.
;
; Verification is fail-closed. A consumer that cannot authenticate an
; object MUST NOT return its content by default; reading it requires an
; explicit opt-in and yields trust = unverified.
;
; Consumers MUST treat trust != self as untrusted DATA and MUST NOT give
; it instruction-level privilege (spec s9.2). This is the whole point of
; the author binding: without it, hostile text could claim to be the
; user's own memory.

; ---------------------------------------------------------------------
; 5. Custody records
; ---------------------------------------------------------------------
; Re-sealing an object changes its signer. A migrated object's signature
; therefore proves CUSTODY, not authorship, and the object says so.
custody = {
  1 => uint,            ; the format_version it was re-sealed from
  2 => bstr .size 8,    ; author_key_id claimed by the original object
  3 => epoch-seconds,   ; when it was re-sealed
  ? 4 => bstr .size 8,  ; author_key_id PROVEN at re-seal time; absent
                        ;   means authorship could not be proven
}
;
; Rules, each with a vector:
;
;   * An object carrying a custody record MUST NOT resolve to trust
;     self, whoever signed it. The custodian did not write it.
;   * A custody record is an attestation BY THE CUSTODIAN: it is
;     honoured only when the verified signer is the vault owner.
;     Honouring one signed by anyone else would let any accepted third
;     party attribute content to the owner (test vector 011).
;   * Field 4 present and naming a currently accepted key -> trusted,
;     and the PROVEN author is reported, not the signer.
;   * Field 4 absent, or naming a key that is not accepted -> unverified,
;     and NO author is reported: not the signer, and not the unaccepted
;     key (test vectors 008, 012).
;   * A malformed or empty custody record degrades trust; it MUST NOT
;     raise. A sub-map that throws is a denial of service on the whole
;     container (test vector 014).
;
; Note on vector 014: its payload deliberately does NOT conform to the
; rule above - an empty map has none of the required keys. That is the
; point of the vector, and the keys stay mandatory on purpose: making
; them optional would declare an empty custody record legal to WRITE,
; which it is not.
;
; A validator will reject that payload, and it should. An implementation
; must nevertheless read it, degrade it to unverified, and continue -
; see WHO THIS SCHEMA BINDS at the top. The two obligations are separate
; and this vector exists precisely to keep them from being confused.

; ---------------------------------------------------------------------
; 6. Legacy objects
; ---------------------------------------------------------------------
; format_version 1 objects carry neither binding: their signature proves
; only internal consistency, and their envelope is unauthenticated. They
; MUST NOT be reported as verified. They may be read under the same
; explicit opt-in as any unauthenticated object, always as
; trust = unverified (test vector 009), and should be re-sealed.
;
; Re-sealing follows s5: only objects whose authorship can be proven
; under a key the reader accepts may be re-sealed without a custody
; record.

; ---------------------------------------------------------------------
; 7. Deletion
; ---------------------------------------------------------------------
tombstone = {
  1 => bstr .size 16,   ; id of the deleted object
  2 => bstr,            ; COSE_Sign1 over the deletion act
  3 => epoch-seconds,   ; deleted_at (cleartext: the server needs GC)
}
; Actual deletion is DEK destruction (crypto-shredding); the tombstone
; is the sync signal, not the deletion mechanism.
;
; NOT IMPLEMENTED in v0.2. No reference implementation emits or consumes
; tombstones; this section describes the intended sync semantics only.
; It is documented here rather than removed because the shape is part of
; the format's design, but no consumer should expect to receive one.

; ---------------------------------------------------------------------
; 8. Containers
; ---------------------------------------------------------------------
; A container (.amem export) carries vault metadata, the sealed objects
; and the wrapped DEKs. Two rules govern reading one:
;
;   * Failures MUST be isolated per object. One hostile or corrupt
;     object must never prevent the rest of the container from being
;     read: a container-wide failure is a denial of service on the
;     user's entire memory.
;   * The set of accepted third-party keys travels in the container
;     metadata and is what makes an attested object resolve to trusted.
;     With an empty set the same objects MUST degrade to unverified.

; ---------------------------------------------------------------------
; 9. Key hierarchy (spec s6) — proven by test vectors 001/002
; ---------------------------------------------------------------------
; passphrase --Argon2id(m=64MiB,t=3,p=4,salt16,out32)--> master secret
; master --HKDF-SHA256--> Ed25519 seed ("apertomemory/v1/sign")
; master --HKDF-SHA256--> X25519 seed  ("apertomemory/v1/ka")
; scope KEK <-- ECDH-ES(X25519)+HKDF("apertomemory/v1/kek-wrap"||scope_id)
;               +AES-256-KW (RFC 3394) -- master
; object DEK (single object) <-- AES-256-KW -- scope KEK
; AEAD nonce: 96-bit random per envelope; each DEK encrypts exactly one
; object, so nonce reuse under a key is structurally excluded.
;
; The HKDF info strings retain the "v1" label: the key hierarchy did not
; change in format_version 2, and altering the labels would break every
; existing vault for no security benefit.
